 alt=E8re notre perception des situations manag=E9riales"
Comment le web alt=E8re - en un sens positif comme n=E9gatif - notre percep=
tion des situations manag=E9riales. Un exemple concret tir=E9 d'une mission=
 d'analyse strat=E9gique et de contre-espionnage =E9conomique dans laquelle=
 la veille internet automatis=E9e joue un r=F4le d=E9terminant dans l'analy=
se des situations tant du point de vue factuel que du point de vue psycholo=
gique, amenant les d=E9cideurs =E0 modifier leur strat=E9gie : Le cas MBT s=
hoes.

- Eddie Soulier - Enseignant-Chercheur - TechCico - "Agr=E9gation d=92activ=
it=E9s, de contenus et d=92objets dans des services mobiles"
L=92agr=E9gation d=92activit=E9s, de contenus et d=92objets dans des servic=
es mobiles qui m=E9lange l=92indispensable aspect social, collaboratif et h=
umain est un nouveau domaine du Web qui marque la prochaine =E9tape de la c=
ollaboration pour augmenter l'interaction et l'innovation. Nous proposons l=
e concept d=92agencement comme un cadre pour formaliser de nouvelles interf=
aces utilisateurs et applications. Les domaines d=92application des agencem=
ents socio-techniques sont l=92Intelligence Territoriale, l=92Ing=E9nierie =
des Syst=E8mes de Services, l=92Intelligence Collective ou le Smart City / =
Smart grid, consid=E9r=E9 comme le fondement d=92une r=E9volution du secteu=
r de l=92Energie. La simulation d=92agencements =E0 l=92aide d=92hypergraph=
es s=92appuie sur les formalismes des complexes simpliciaux ou la m=E9r=E9o=
logie. Son objectif est d=92offrir de nouveaux outils d=92aide =E0 la d=E9c=
ision aux usagers comme aux d=E9cideurs.

- Julie Dugdale - Enseignant-Chercheur - LIG -  "Social media and SMS in cr=
isis situations"
In recent years our society has seen the enormous growth and popularity of =
social media sites such as FaceBook and Twitter. These, coupled with the in=
creased use of smart phones and other mobile devices, have radically change=
d the way that individuals interact and communicate. Within the crisis mana=
gement domain these tools are being adopted and exploited by both crisis ma=
nagers and citizens alike. Recent large-scale emergencies, such as the Hait=
i Earthquake gave rise to an unprecedented surge of citizen involvement whe=
re humanitarian workers tried to cope with massive amounts of information p=
rovided by citizens through web portals, platforms, and new social networki=
ng media, such as SMS feeds, Twitter, etc. Such is the increase of citizen =
participation that current crisis management information systems, e.g. the =
SAHANA Open Source Disaster Management System and the crowd-sourcing platfo=
rm Ushaidi, now purposely provide ways to incorporate information sent by c=
itizens through social media and SMS. This presentation will examine the us=
e and applicability of social media in crisis management from both the citi=
zens and crisis managers=92 point of view, and explore some of the challeng=
es faced by its adoption.


