iv><b><br></b></div><div><b>- Julie Dugdale&nbsp;</b><b>- Enseignant-Cherch=
eur&nbsp;</b><b>- LIG -&nbsp;&nbsp;"Social media and SMS in crisis situatio=
ns"</b></div><div>In recent years our&nbsp;society has seen the enormous gr=
owth and popularity of social media sites such&nbsp;as FaceBook and Twitter=
. These, coupled with the&nbsp;increased use of smart phones&nbsp;and other=
 mobile devices, have radically changed the way that individuals interact&n=
bsp;and communicate. Within the crisis&nbsp;management domain these tools a=
re being&nbsp;adopted and exploited by both crisis managers and citizens al=
ike. Recent&nbsp;large-scale emergencies, such as&nbsp;the Haiti Earthquake=
 gave rise to an&nbsp;unprecedented surge of citizen involvement where huma=
nitarian workers tried to&nbsp;cope with massive amounts of&nbsp;informatio=
n provided by citizens through web&nbsp;portals, platforms, and new social =
networking media, such as SMS feeds,&nbsp;Twitter, etc. Such is the&nbsp;in=
crease of citizen participation that current crisis&nbsp;management informa=
tion systems, e.g. the SAHANA Open Source Disaster Management&nbsp;System a=
nd&nbsp;the crowd-sourcing platform Ushaidi, now purposely provide ways to&=
nbsp;incorporate information sent by citizens through social media and SMS.=
 This&nbsp;presentation&nbsp;will examine the use and applicability of soci=
al media in crisis management&nbsp;from both the citizens and crisis manage=
rs=92 point of view,&nbsp;and explore some of&nbsp;the challenges faced by =
its adoption.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div>
